pullRequest.body:
This PR proves the [Akra-Bazzi theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akra%E2%80%93Bazzi_method), which gives the asymptotic order of divide-and-conquer recurrences of the form
```
T n = (∑ i in Fin k, a i * T (r i n)) + g n
```
where `T : ℕ → ℝ`, and where `r i n` is close to `b i * n` for a set of coefficients `b : Fin k → ℝ`. These recurrences arise mainly in the analysis of divide-and-conquer algorithms such as mergesort or Strassen's algorithm for matrix multiplication.

Note that the traditional proof first proves a continuous version (i.e. for `T : ℝ → ℝ`) and then discretizes it to get a version that is relevant for algorithms. Here we prove the discrete version directly, which shortens the proof considerably.

you have a small o here, but Wikipedia gives the claim with a big O. Which is correct?

It can be tightened to big-O, by choosing the "smoothing function" differently and making the proof more complicated. This would have a very low payoff though, I'm not sure there is even a single application where this makes a difference, `o(n / (log n)^2)` is already overkill most of the time.

Can you explain briefly in the docstring why you choose to use a real number parameter and not an integer one while the algorithm only makes sense at integer values?

Do I understand correctly that it would suffice to require this for `b=1/2`, say (or just any `b < 1`) (because iterating twice you get it for `(1/2)^2`, and then `(1/2)^n`, and this is arbitrarily small as `n` tends to infinity). Of course, all these are equivalent so you may pick the definition you prefer, but it might be worth mentioning this in the docstring, and also giving specific constructors. (It's not clear to me if the proofs below would be more convenient with the other definition, or if it wouldn't make any real difference). Isn't it also equivalent to the fact that the bound holds between `x` and `2 x`, say?

Yes, you're correct, and I actually considered defining it for `b = 1/2`. I went with this version because the `b = 1/2` version doesn't make any of the proofs easier, and it's the version we actually want to use anyway.
